Current implementation is wrong because `this.seed1 = SOMETHING() + this.seed0;` makes the seeds highly correlated on each random generation. The correct code is

``` java
this.seed1 = SOMETHING();
return this.seed1 + this.seed0;
```

Also I've overridden all `nextXXX()` methods so to make them use `nextLong()` instead of `next()` which returns an int value. This way methods like `nextLong()` and `nextDouble()` can internally use only one random long instead of two random long casted to int and then appended.

http://stackoverflow.com/questions/24632095/how-to-rotate-decal-over-more-then-one-axis-at-moment

It looks like currently the only way to set a rotation on all axes at the same time is via a workaround like this:

```
decal.setRotationX(0);
decal.setRotationY(0);
decal.setRotationZ(0);
decal.rotateX(angleX);
decal.rotateY(angleY);
decal.rotateZ(angleZ);
```

Or the shorter but more ugly version:

```
decal.setRotationX(angleX);
decal.rotateY(angleY);
decal.rotateZ(angleZ);
```

That's why I added a `Decal.setRotation(...)` method which can set all angles at once.

Hello,
I have one GC-related issue when using Box2D-shapes in libGDX.

There is this message in the Shape.java class
https://github.com/greysonp/GameFramework/blob/c1b79ca502ca8a3dbeed65aab7c6ad2637348a6b/src/com/badlogic/gdx/physics/box2d/Shape.java

saying: "NOTE: YOU NEED TO DISPOSE SHAPES YOU CREATED YOURSELF AFTER YOU NO LONGER USE THEM"

Ok, I discovered the dispose() method recycling C++ shape instance:
public void dispose () {
        jniDispose(addr);
    }

However, what am I supposed to do with the Java shape instance then?

Cheking CircleShape.java and PolygonShape.java
/*\* Constructs a new polygon */
    public PolygonShape () {
        addr = newPolygonShape();// <----- C++ call
    }

shows that the Java instances of these classes are not re-usable anymore. I guess the only option left to me here is to throw the shape instance at the wind. It concerns me because such a move will provoke GC (when I create/dispose a lot of Box2D-objects) and this is what I want to avoid during a game action.

How can I compress a Pixmap? I want to save it on the disk, but it uses about 4MB, which is way to much and takes like forever to save it.

```
final Pixmap pixmap = ScreenUtils.getFrameBufferPixmap(x, y, w, h);
FileHandle screenshot = Gdx.files.local("something.png");
PixmapIO.writePNG(screenshot, pixmap);
```

I saw that there is an `PixmapIO.writeCIM`, which is quite fast and the output is quite small.

Am I able to display the `something.cim` file in Android? The [docu](http://libgdx.badlogicgames.com/nightlies/docs/api/com/badlogic/gdx/graphics/PixmapIO.html) says, that cim should only be used within libgdx. Arguing that this is the old documentation, maybe there is something new?

Hello there good chaps,

LibGDX game on Android, sometimes when switching back to app this happens:
http://imgur.com/vxgYTmA
But it should look like this: http://imgur.com/jycK5Dv

It happens on many devices (low-end Android 2.3 and high-end 4.4) and I am unable to replicate the conditions required for this bug to happen. I've researched this for quite a long time, and found info about the OpenGL context loss - but there are no dynamically generated textures here, I am loading a TextureAtlas packed by TexturePacker, via

``` java
// async loading
assets.load("data/fonts/visitor26.fnt", BitmapFont.class);
assets.load("data/fonts/visitor52.fnt", BitmapFont.class);
assets.load("data/fonts/visitor128.fnt", BitmapFont.class);

TextureAtlasParameter param = new TextureAtlasParameter();
param.flip = true;
assets.load("data/tex/demonteeth.pack", TextureAtlas.class, param);
assets.load("data/tex/sprites.pack", TextureAtlas.class, param);
```

If I am correct, textures should be now managed by LibGDX.
Then, of course, i'm getting TextureAtlases objects to extract sprites later:

``` java
visitor26 = assets.get("data/fonts/visitor26.fnt", BitmapFont.class);
visitor52 = assets.get("data/fonts/visitor52.fnt", BitmapFont.class);
visitor128 = assets.get("data/fonts/visitor128.fnt", BitmapFont.class);
bg = assets.get("data/tex/demonteeth.pack", TextureAtlas.class);
sprites = assets.get("data/tex/sprites.pack", TextureAtlas.class);
```

The class that holds the TextureAtlases IS NOT static (as I've read that causes problems on Android) and I re-create it if it's lost - by invoking this method in onStart() and onResume() in my libgdx app

``` java
public static void restoreRenderer(Camera camera, Camera fontcamera) {
        if (r==null){
        r = new Renderer();
        }
        r.setCamera(camera);
        r.setFontCamera(fontcamera);
    }
```

..but the Renderer object itself is held in a static field in the main game class:

``` java
public class Core {
    public static Renderer r;
//moar code
}
```

My ultimate question to awesome libgdx devs: is there any way to detect OpenGL context loss? If that's possible, I would simply force reloading of the TextureAtlases :) I've researched this issue, but found no cure for this... Wiki also is silent :(

Xoxo, and have a nice day!
